anova(mod_red, mod_full)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: mcsa ~ unr_20to64 + pr_f + me_2018 + one_race_b + one_race_i + 
##     one_race_a + one_race_h + one_race_other + two_races + hispanic + 
##     households + emp_service + emp_sales + emp_n + emp_p
## Model 2: mcsa ~ unr_16 + unr_20to64 + pr_f + pr_p + mhi_2018 + me_2018 + 
##     total_pop + one_race + one_race_w + one_race_b + one_race_i + 
##     one_race_a + one_race_h + one_race_other + two_races + hispanic + 
##     households + h_under6_both_work + h_6to17_both_work + emp_m + 
##     emp_service + emp_sales + emp_n + emp_p
##   Res.Df      RSS Df Sum of Sq      F    Pr(>F)    
## 1  23577 19014029                                  
## 2  23568 18193265  9    820763 118.14 < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

\(F = 129.17\), \(p < 2.2 \times 10^{-16}\), so we reject \(H_0\) and we conclude that the variables with the highest VIF (one_race, emp_m, one_race_w, total_pop, h_under6_both_work, h_6to17_both_work, unr_16, pr_p, and mhi_2018) is not statistically significantly if all of the other explanatory variable are included in the model.

Adding interaction, quadratic, log, and/or sqrt terms to model

# adding interaction terms: 
mod_red_inter <- lm(log(mcsa) ~ unr_20to64 + pr_f + me_2018 + one_race_b*one_race_i + one_race_a*one_race_h + one_race_other*two_races + hispanic + households + emp_service*emp_sales + emp_n*emp_p ,childcare)

# adding quadratic terms to model
mod_red_quad <- lm(mcsa ~ unr_20to64^2 + pr_f^2 + me_2018^2 + one_race_b + one_race_i + one_race_a + one_race_h + one_race_other + two_races + hispanic + households + emp_service + emp_sales + emp_n + emp_p ,childcare)

# QQ and Residual plots to analyze each model: 
#plot(mod_red_inter, 1)
#plot(mod_red_inter, 2)
#summary(mod_red_inter)

# summary of full and reduced models
summary(mod_full)

## Multiple R-squared:  0.7128, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7125 
## F-statistic:  2412 on 24 and 23317 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Hypotheses and Conclusion \[H_0: \beta_2 = \beta_3 = {...} = \beta_{53}= 0\]

\[H_a: \text{At least one } \beta \neq 0\]

\(F = 2412\), \(p < 2.2 \times 10^{-16}\), so we reject \(H_0\) and conclude that adding a logarithmic model and interaction terms between the various race and employment variables to our regression model is statistically significant.
